00:05:51,880 --> 00:05:52,360
been a shift.

93
00:05:52,720 --> 00:05:56,962
You know, we've seen new games all the time that are challenging the established assumption

94
00:05:57,342 --> 00:05:59,502
about what happens when a player fails.

95
00:06:00,903 --> 00:06:05,284
But we can think of these as approaches that are trying to kind of sweeten the deal for

96
00:06:05,304 --> 00:06:05,684
the player.

97
00:06:05,704 --> 00:06:06,604
Right?

98
00:06:07,065 --> 00:06:11,806
They're still dealing with the currency of player time, but doing it in a way of, that's

99
00:06:11,846 --> 00:06:13,687
kind of, it's because it's a way of offloading the problem.

100
00:06:15,686 --> 00:06:19,849
So trying to apply some multiplier to the failures effects on the game and make sure

101
00:06:19,869 --> 00:06:24,773
that it's worth more than just lost time and also at the same time start to bring back

102
00:06:24,833 --> 00:06:26,555
some of those consequences into the game state.

103
00:06:27,155 --> 00:06:28,136
So what are some examples of that?

104
00:06:30,083 --> 00:06:34,507
So we see in kind of persistent world games and in MMOs this kind of commitment to the

