00:10:52,872 --> 00:10:56,014
So when we talk about setbacks, just to be clear...

177
00:10:57,002 --> 00:11:00,563
You know, these are arising out of the game's low-level mechanics.

178
00:11:01,423 --> 00:11:03,644
It's not something we design into the map.

179
00:11:05,424 --> 00:11:11,446
We're talking about something that is not a forced mode change, it's not an exotic gameplay

180
00:11:11,466 --> 00:11:15,047
sequence, it's not a scripted moment where Nathan Drake is tossed out of the back of

181
00:11:15,107 --> 00:11:19,068
a cargo plane in mid-air, even though that obviously fits the narrative definition of

182
00:11:19,108 --> 00:11:19,548
a setback.

183
00:11:19,628 --> 00:11:20,328
That's not what we mean.

184
00:11:23,162 --> 00:11:25,845
We're talking about a prolonged period of gameplay.

185
00:11:26,746 --> 00:11:30,529
And it arises from the same systems that the player's using the rest of the time.

186
00:11:31,891 --> 00:11:35,254
It's preventing runaway behavior, but it's still allowing play to continue,

187
00:11:35,534 --> 00:11:36,075
survivably.

188
00:11:37,416 --> 00:11:42,060
And it's perceptibly altering the state of the game in some meaningful way.

189
00:11:42,821 --> 00:11:43,302
It's interesting.

190
00:11:45,956 --> 00:11:51,703
So this experience, if we want to think of it aesthetically, is directly analogous actually

