00:14:14,773 --> 00:14:17,796
It also needs to revise the player's awareness of the

234
00:14:17,836 --> 00:14:19,757
game's state or context.

235
00:14:22,313 --> 00:14:26,738
In other words, a setback can be defined as that moment when the player's immediate goal

236
00:14:26,898 --> 00:14:28,360
changes unexpectedly.

237
00:14:33,344 --> 00:14:38,590
That says that setbacks are built out of the switching off between what the player thought

238
00:14:38,630 --> 00:14:39,471
they were going to be doing...

239
00:14:40,604 --> 00:14:43,986
and a new priority that's absolutely critical to the continuation of play.

240
00:14:44,707 --> 00:14:48,229
So if we can work with that definition right away, we can start to understand the scope

241
00:14:48,629 --> 00:14:52,172
of potential setbacks in terms of a broader system of player goals.

242
00:14:53,453 --> 00:14:59,117
So, luckily, there's a lot of work out there that establishes general taxonomies of player goals,

243
00:14:59,217 --> 00:15:00,938
and the good news is they're mostly pretty finite.

244
00:15:01,739 --> 00:15:05,661
Lots of people are already familiar with Bjork and Halperin's patterns in game design,

245
00:15:05,682 --> 00:15:07,863
so I've kind of adapted the list that they use.

246
00:15:07,923 --> 00:15:09,344
There's 13 goals that they talk about.

247
00:15:09,364 --> 00:15:10,005
This is them.

248
00:15:10,663 --> 00:15:11,364
Yeah, there they come.

249
00:15:12,284 --> 00:15:15,304
I've re-termed them a little bit to put them in verb form.

250
00:15:15,865 --> 00:15:18,165
But out of these 13, what's interesting

251
00:15:18,245 --> 00:15:20,826
is, if you just start with the transitions that

252
00:15:20,866 --> 00:15:22,946
go from a single goal A to a single goal B

253
00:15:23,206 --> 00:15:25,587
and from that same goal B back to goal A,

254
00:15:25,667 --> 00:15:27,327
because for our purposes, those are distinct,

255
00:15:27,887 --> 00:15:28,927
out of those 13 goals, you're going

256
00:15:28,967 --> 00:15:31,468
to get about 650 unique transitions.

257
00:15:31,848 --> 00:15:32,768
A little more, a little less, I don't know.

258
00:15:33,408 --> 00:15:34,149
That's not too many.

259
00:15:34,169 --> 00:15:36,349
And out of those, we only really care

260
00:15:36,389 --> 00:15:38,550
about the subset that's systemic, recoverable,

261
00:15:38,570 --> 00:15:38,990
and interesting.

262
00:15:41,292 --> 00:15:44,154
but also the ones that keep the player in the sweet spot

263
00:15:44,474 --> 00:15:46,215
between wanting to quit the game and trade it in

264
00:15:47,676 --> 00:15:49,897
or being so inconsequential as to get lost

265
00:15:50,358 --> 00:15:54,060
in the noise of moment-to-moment challenge.

266
00:15:54,640 --> 00:15:56,821
So that's an interesting model, but it's still too abstract.

267
00:15:57,882 --> 00:16:00,703
I want to try applying it to the types of games I'm the most familiar with.

268
00:16:01,084 --> 00:16:02,945
So I want to look at the stealth genre. I want to look at

269
00:16:03,365 --> 00:16:06,006
failure in stealth games, which typically looks like this.

270
00:16:09,790 --> 00:16:13,154
So classically, stealth games have relied on four key pillars.

271
00:16:13,735 --> 00:16:17,479
You've got the fragility of the game state, the fact that the game starts the player out

272
00:16:17,920 --> 00:16:20,062
undetected by the game's ecosystems,

273
00:16:20,543 --> 00:16:23,906
and the player's challenge is to try to preserve that state moving forward.

274
00:16:26,052 --> 00:16:29,997
there's the fact that that ecosystem is a simulation, right?

275
00:16:30,618 --> 00:16:32,240
It exists independently of the player.

276
00:16:32,881 --> 00:16:34,283
It's analog for the most part.

277
00:16:34,603 --> 00:16:36,766
So the player needs to use their intuition,

278
00:16:36,786 --> 00:16:39,350
their observational skills, in order to read the AI,

279
00:16:39,390 --> 00:16:40,471
in order to read the environment

280
00:16:40,832 --> 00:16:42,334
and understand the gameplay potential there.

281
00:16:43,399 --> 00:16:47,442
And the player is really incentivized to do that by the fact that they're not very powerful,

282
00:16:47,723 --> 00:16:49,264
typically, in the kind of classical model.

283
00:16:49,284 --> 00:16:55,209
The game imposes, often, survival horror levels of scarcity in terms of resources, in terms

284
00:16:55,229 --> 00:16:59,152
of ammunition and health and all of the other resources at the player's disposal.

285
00:17:00,033 --> 00:17:03,075
And if they do get into a fight, they're better off running away, typically.

286
00:17:05,577 --> 00:17:06,898
Now the flip side to that...

287
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:10,923
is that if these games are richly systemic as they often are,

288
00:17:11,623 --> 00:17:13,064
they're typically pretty high agency.

289
00:17:14,325 --> 00:17:18,388
Players are afforded a lot of tools and opportunities for playing with the AI

290
00:17:18,788 --> 00:17:21,410
and finding creative solutions to get through a problem.

291
00:17:23,416 --> 00:17:28,037
Now, the classical hardship of stealth, though, was always that almost anything the player

292
00:17:28,077 --> 00:17:29,598
does disturbs the system.

293
00:17:30,818 --> 00:17:35,239
And once the player falls off that, what's called the detection cliff, it's hard to support

294
00:17:35,259 --> 00:17:37,019
many ways for them to continue moving forward.

295
00:17:37,700 --> 00:17:42,481
It forces the player, ultimately, to be a perfectionist, sometimes literally by returning

296
00:17:42,501 --> 00:17:48,262
the game over if an alarm is tripped, or, at best, forcing the player to make a run

297
00:17:48,322 --> 00:17:48,522
for it.

298
00:17:50,163 --> 00:17:50,263
So...

299
00:17:51,766 --> 00:17:56,070
The early solution to that has been to go through some kind of strange contortions to

300
00:17:56,131 --> 00:17:57,692
limit the player's exposure.

301
00:17:58,373 --> 00:18:02,597
That leads to some sort of arbitrary level design solutions like resetting the AI after

302
00:18:02,697 --> 00:18:03,899
each section.

303
00:18:05,100 --> 00:18:07,082
And that doesn't really encourage experimentation.

304
00:18:09,066 --> 00:18:13,371
So that model of stealth maps to these kinds of goal transitions.

305
00:18:13,651 --> 00:18:17,255
So this is classical stealth in terms of goal transitions the way I was describing it.

306
00:18:17,675 --> 00:18:22,741
So from this initial state, the player either needs to explore the world in order to reveal

307
00:18:23,161 --> 00:18:26,905
the various objectives available to them, or maybe because it's on some kind of formal

308
00:18:26,945 --> 00:18:28,847
mission structure, they just need to get from A to B.

309
00:18:29,027 --> 00:18:30,429
They just need to get into the mission space.

310
00:18:31,045 --> 00:18:35,586
And then from there, they need to align themselves to be able to go through a collection of objectives,

311
00:18:35,686 --> 00:18:39,187
some of which are probably mandatory, some of which may be optional.

312
00:18:40,067 --> 00:18:45,269
And the main disruption occurs when they come into first contact with the enemy and have

313
00:18:45,289 --> 00:18:46,589
to get past them undetected.

314
00:18:46,629 --> 00:18:50,470
They need to paint some kind of picture of the state of the game and understand where

315
00:18:50,490 --> 00:18:51,731
the enemy is at and what they're doing.

316
00:18:52,291 --> 00:18:58,312
Which leads to, usually, some fairly trivial goal shifting, either to realign or to maybe

317
00:18:58,332 --> 00:18:59,413
get to some kind of safe haven.

318
00:19:01,607 --> 00:19:08,894
And this is notable because for much of play in this kind of game, doing nothing is actually

319
00:19:08,914 --> 00:19:09,855
a really good strategy.

320
00:19:11,116 --> 00:19:13,939
And the player has these kind of extended periods of stimulated planning.

321
00:19:15,060 --> 00:19:16,241
Not exactly action-packed.

322
00:19:17,322 --> 00:19:20,825
And when there is a major setback, frankly, it almost collapses the game entirely, and

323
00:19:20,845 --> 00:19:24,188
assuming that it's not a straight-up game over, the player's probably booking it.

324
00:19:26,464 --> 00:19:32,368
Okay, so what we'd like to do is let the player recover from those kinds of situations and

325
00:19:32,428 --> 00:19:36,091
restore the game to a condition where they're hidden, where they're back to being stealthy

326
00:19:36,191 --> 00:19:37,292
and they're doing what they like to do.

327
00:19:38,172 --> 00:19:39,873
And we want them to be able to do that systemically.

328
00:19:42,415 --> 00:19:46,998
Jamming open the detection window by preventing a single instance of the AI from wrecking

329
00:19:47,038 --> 00:19:50,461
everything and from propagating that detection to the rest of the world.

330
00:19:51,235 --> 00:19:57,296
We want to assume that if you're some kind of elite spy or thief or assassin or hitman,

331
00:19:58,016 --> 00:20:01,897
that you have it in your ability to take out that one stupid guy that's going to sound

332
00:20:01,937 --> 00:20:06,158
the alarm and kind of climb your way back up the detection cliff in order to get into

333
00:20:06,198 --> 00:20:06,798
a state of stealth.

334
00:20:08,659 --> 00:20:08,839
Alright.

335
00:20:10,299 --> 00:20:13,540
So for the rest of the talk, what we're going to do is we're going to kind of...

336
00:20:14,734 --> 00:20:19,237
go through and look at kinds of gameplay models that are doing what I'm talking about.

337
00:20:19,497 --> 00:20:20,958
We're going to look at recovery dynamics.

338
00:20:21,638 --> 00:20:22,839
And there are a lot of different ways

339
00:20:22,859 --> 00:20:24,900
that players try to modulate

340
00:20:25,360 --> 00:20:28,162
their ability, sort of the games try to modulate the player's ability

341
00:20:28,542 --> 00:20:29,003
to recover.

342
00:20:29,603 --> 00:20:32,725
And when we look at them in terms of goal transitions, it starts to become clear

343
00:20:33,245 --> 00:20:35,947
which strategies do a good job of exposing the player

344
00:20:36,327 --> 00:20:37,087
to good setbacks.

345
00:20:38,688 --> 00:20:39,309
And which ones don't.

346
00:20:42,612 --> 00:20:45,813
The Save Anywhere model is going to be familiar to anybody who's been playing a lot of Skyrim

347
00:20:45,833 --> 00:20:46,313
on PC.

348
00:20:46,933 --> 00:20:47,093
Right?

349
00:20:47,573 --> 00:20:50,334
You've been writing the quick save, quick load buttons, you know.

350
00:20:50,854 --> 00:20:54,815
This can be satisfying, I mean, it's in its own way, but make no mistake, it degenerates

351
00:20:54,855 --> 00:20:55,175
the game.

352
00:20:55,195 --> 00:20:55,756
Right?

353
00:20:56,116 --> 00:21:01,437
In terms of our model, it effectively reduces any situation in the game to incremental experimentation.

354
00:21:01,877 --> 00:21:04,078
And that is a valid way to play that game.

355
00:21:07,007 --> 00:21:09,528
But it does quickly hollow out whatever sense of context

356
00:21:09,568 --> 00:21:10,689
the player has over time.

357
00:21:11,549 --> 00:21:13,550
And it renders it mostly inconsequential

358
00:21:13,790 --> 00:21:14,691
in the context of the game.

359
00:21:16,752 --> 00:21:20,314
Unfortunately, the console-friendly flip side

360
00:21:20,354 --> 00:21:22,015
of that doesn't fare a whole lot better.

361
00:21:23,676 --> 00:21:25,857
In this case, the player in a corridor shooter

362
00:21:25,897 --> 00:21:28,459
simply has to endure the designer's intentions

363
00:21:29,019 --> 00:21:30,460
and reach the next trigger volume.

364
00:21:32,301 --> 00:21:34,882
In fact, they might not actually have to do anything else.

365
00:21:35,002 --> 00:21:36,623
They might not have to fire a shot.

366
00:21:37,982 --> 00:21:44,024
Again, that act of traversal to get from point A to point B effectively collapses the game

367
00:21:44,344 --> 00:21:49,506
into a challenge that totally undermines the mechanical tension.

368
00:21:53,427 --> 00:21:58,509
So another solution is for games to deliver what's really kind of a thousand foot view

369
00:21:58,629 --> 00:22:02,010
on the game world, accompanied by kind of a rich information layer.

370
00:22:02,798 --> 00:22:06,482
If you compare Clay's Mark of the Ninja with, for example, Dishonored,

371
00:22:07,183 --> 00:22:09,445
two games that share several core mechanics,

372
00:22:10,026 --> 00:22:12,669
the side-scrolling format means that players can see

373
00:22:12,689 --> 00:22:16,432
exactly what part of the world they can disturb.

374
00:22:17,053 --> 00:22:19,836
And they have a lot of UI tools for monitoring the state of the AI,

375
00:22:19,996 --> 00:22:23,019
even when they're obscured, when they're hidden behind a wall or a door.

376
00:22:25,681 --> 00:22:29,805
And when something does happen that disrupts the player's intentions, it slips the game

377
00:22:29,865 --> 00:22:31,666
back into a goal of alignment.

378
00:22:32,207 --> 00:22:34,729
And so this has a kind of interesting effect.

379
00:22:34,749 --> 00:22:39,393
It sort of, having such a complete tactical picture of the world around you effectively

380
00:22:39,473 --> 00:22:43,817
turns the game into kind of a strategy game, even though it's, you know, it's this 2D side-scrolling

381
00:22:43,857 --> 00:22:44,898
platforming stealth experience.

382
00:22:45,719 --> 00:22:48,482
And you know, Mark of the Ninja is a hugely satisfying game.

383
00:22:48,602 --> 00:22:52,625
It just, it happens to rely on a different mechanism in order to deliver.

384
00:22:53,280 --> 00:22:55,443
that sense of setback. It's not coming from

385
00:22:56,104 --> 00:22:59,528
necessarily a lack of information the way it would in a more immersive style

386
00:22:59,568 --> 00:23:00,950
of stealth game.

387
00:23:01,210 --> 00:23:01,871
And plus which,

388
00:23:02,372 --> 00:23:05,836
because of the format that it uses, there is a more rapid turnaround when you fail

389
00:23:05,876 --> 00:23:06,517
and need to reload.

390
00:23:07,118 --> 00:23:09,000
So it isn't punishing in that respect.

391
00:23:12,263 --> 00:23:16,066
You know we talked earlier about how we put a premium on the consistency of the player experience

392
00:23:16,786 --> 00:23:23,330
but some games will change the rules on the fly as a hedge against players selling short when the chips are down

393
00:23:23,710 --> 00:23:27,813
and so they basically stated that that consistency is not as important as trying to keep the player in the game

394
00:23:28,173 --> 00:23:29,013
and that's a valid choice.

395
00:23:30,572 --> 00:23:33,874
You can sort of see the carrot version of this with fighting games that feature damage

396
00:23:33,894 --> 00:23:35,996
scaling or some kind of desperation mode.

397
00:23:36,856 --> 00:23:43,341
And ultimately, what happens is the player learns over time that the trick is to absorb

398
00:23:43,501 --> 00:23:47,144
punishment until the game delivers them the means of recovery.

399
00:23:48,785 --> 00:23:53,509
And the effect of that is, again, to reduce the sense of consequence to the game.

400
00:23:56,125 --> 00:24:00,286
The stick version of that can be seen in games that use some kind of token-based damage system

401
00:24:00,686 --> 00:24:05,088
so that players that are in an otherwise skill-based game can end up suffering certain kinds of

402
00:24:05,128 --> 00:24:06,308
setbacks deterministically.

403
00:24:06,828 --> 00:24:11,670
So to use a stealth example, AI enemies in the Batman Arkham games who will start targeting

404
00:24:11,710 --> 00:24:15,391
destructible gargoyles in challenge rooms as a way of interfering with the player's

405
00:24:15,811 --> 00:24:18,492
ability to maneuver and use the kind of Batman swinging around.

406
00:24:20,347 --> 00:24:24,448
Well, the mechanism is the same, but actually the player's perception of it is the polar

407
00:24:24,528 --> 00:24:27,949
opposite because in their view the game has taken something away from them and now it

408
00:24:27,969 --> 00:24:29,170
takes them time to get it back.

409
00:24:29,590 --> 00:24:35,852
So in that case, the perception is that it's pushing against them, it's frustrating or

410
00:24:35,952 --> 00:24:37,972
foiling their attempts to do the thing that they want to do.

411
00:24:40,213 --> 00:24:42,114
So those kinds of tweaks need to be applied conservatively.

412
00:24:42,454 --> 00:24:46,255
So I want to talk for a second about the example of Dungeons of the Endless.

413
00:24:47,330 --> 00:24:49,732
This is interesting, right? We have this sort of roguelike experience

414
00:24:50,272 --> 00:24:54,456
where the players need to manage limited resources in order to get to the exit, if you will,

415
00:24:54,476 --> 00:24:55,837
of the current section that they're in.

416
00:24:56,657 --> 00:24:57,538
That's pretty straightforward.

417
00:24:57,758 --> 00:25:01,101
What spices it up is the fact that then we have these additional rooms

418
00:25:01,401 --> 00:25:02,662
that are kind of these mystery boxes.

419
00:25:03,383 --> 00:25:07,306
And the risk-reward trade-off is by opening some of them up,

420
00:25:07,366 --> 00:25:09,388
you can potentially add to your resource pool, but

421
00:25:09,668 --> 00:25:12,170
you can also unleash additional horrors

422
00:25:12,590 --> 00:25:14,452
on top of the ones that are already standing in your path.

423
00:25:15,666 --> 00:25:18,647
And so this generates a fair amount of tension in a very simple way.

424
00:25:18,687 --> 00:25:23,350
Now what's interesting is the simplest kind of tension economy is really just in a sports

425
00:25:23,370 --> 00:25:23,550
game.

426
00:25:23,770 --> 00:25:27,532
It's when you have two teams that are both scoring points at the same time.

427
00:25:29,513 --> 00:25:29,613
So

428
00:25:30,573 --> 00:25:35,696
this type of approach applies to a number of different games. It's very interesting to see that it crosses a lot of genre boundaries.

429
00:25:36,417 --> 00:25:40,860
That kind of simple Red Queen scenario, with the kind of moving goalposts,

430
00:25:41,360 --> 00:25:46,704
forces or pressures the player to switch goals when the point deficit between them and the other side gets too big.

431
00:25:47,605 --> 00:25:50,427
So that would be what we'd call a single-axis tension economy.

432
00:25:51,267 --> 00:25:55,810
The points can go up, the point spread can go down, but whether I have four points or twelve points...

433
00:25:56,691 --> 00:25:59,312
matters only in terms of how many points the other side has.

434
00:25:59,792 --> 00:26:01,593
Right, and so that sets the context for the game.

435
00:26:03,233 --> 00:26:05,454
What that means in terms of goal transitions is that

436
00:26:05,634 --> 00:26:09,035
it forces the player to abandon the kind of luxury objectives,

437
00:26:09,335 --> 00:26:12,056
you know, the collection of objectives you kind of see on the far left over there,

438
00:26:12,316 --> 00:26:14,117
in favor of the most expedient goals,

439
00:26:14,477 --> 00:26:16,498
such as taking the opposing force out of play,

440
00:26:17,058 --> 00:26:18,598
or going all-in on the main prize.

441
00:26:20,419 --> 00:26:20,519
Now...

442
00:26:21,377 --> 00:26:25,300
you get a more nuanced output in tension economies when you add a second economy

443
00:26:25,700 --> 00:26:29,883
that just consists of time that's slowly chipping away.

444
00:26:30,923 --> 00:26:33,625
So you can take a game like Rim Capsule, which is real time,

445
00:26:33,665 --> 00:26:37,368
the player has to watch the clock, they're frantically completing all of these critical tasks.

446
00:26:37,608 --> 00:26:40,712
you know, building their bases, scanning their monoliths, all the stuff that they gotta get

447
00:26:40,752 --> 00:26:41,853
done within 45 minutes.

448
00:26:43,435 --> 00:26:47,320
And then just waiting for that exact moment to like pull back into defensive positions

449
00:26:47,360 --> 00:26:51,205
because the next big wave, increasingly large wave of enemies is gonna come in and try to

450
00:26:51,245 --> 00:26:52,126
mitigate the effects of that.

451
00:26:54,508 --> 00:26:58,571
It works in a turn-based game as well. So you can take Invisible Inc., the game formerly

452
00:26:58,852 --> 00:27:05,116
known as Incognita, and every time the player's little team of spies makes a move, it's depleting

453
00:27:05,256 --> 00:27:09,359
one little tick from this kind of finite pool of time that's available to them to complete

454
00:27:09,399 --> 00:27:14,123
the mission. And so when it hits zero, the whole map goes into alert, and suddenly the

455
00:27:14,163 --> 00:27:18,786
reinforcements show up hot on your heels. And so this puts an interesting counter-pressure

456
00:27:18,826 --> 00:27:21,628
on the player, where they have to decide how greedy they want to be.

457
00:27:22,429 --> 00:27:26,271
They have to decide how many of these juicy optional objectives that are available to them

458
00:27:26,311 --> 00:27:27,431
they want to try to go after.

459
00:27:27,451 --> 00:27:31,334
And of course they're willing to overextend themselves a little bit each time

460
00:27:31,594 --> 00:27:34,335
when they know that the SWAT guys are coming in through the main doors

461
00:27:34,355 --> 00:27:35,656
and are going to chase them down to the exit.

462
00:27:38,496 --> 00:27:43,824
And so, with the addition of that second economy, it kind of brings the dynamics of the game more fully into view.

463
00:27:43,924 --> 00:27:48,151
And what you're seeing is that it adds this layer of suspense to the player's decision-making,

464
00:27:48,391 --> 00:27:52,718
because it's no longer feasible for the player to succeed just through simple attrition.

